    # [Scene: Seawall Construction Site | Morning — Overcast, wind chopping the air]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Mechanical percussion layered with distant, anxious strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Metal on metal; diesel engines coughing; the sea’s low, inexorable roar]
    "You watch the first panel lift into place like a flat, obedient tooth being set into a jaw. You authorized this — your pen, your signature, the authorization that turned models and meetings into cranes and"
    "concrete. The memory of the conference room is a bright, clinical cut behind your ribs; here, the work is loud and immediate and impossible to un-say."
    "Salt stings your nostrils. The wind grabs at your field jacket until the embroidered tide lines ripple like a small flag. Your leather notebook is under your arm, pages clacking with the rhythm of the machinery,"
    "maps fluttering like nervous birds. You can feel, with a disciplinary clarity that the morning light refuses to warm, the difference between what you hoped would happen and what actually is: perfect vertical panels, stainless joints,"
    "a line that promises to keep water where it belongs and deny it access to the wharves that have been eaten by storms in years past."
    show mayor_lynette_cole at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_lynette_cole "Citizens of Brinehaven — today we mark not only a new seawall, but a new era. Investment. Safety. Jobs."
    show cassian_cass_romano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "A lot of people worked hard for months to make sure this was engineered for the tide lines and for our models to be adaptive."
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Jobs that look like ours. Don't let the shiny parts take that away."

    cassian_cass_romano "We're binding labor assurances into the contract. Local crews first. Transparent audits."

    jonah_reyes "Drafts read good on paper, Cass."
    "Words bounce off the girders like wind. The ribbon sits at the edge of the concrete slab — ceremonial, fragile — and the cameras angle in, hungry for a sequence: a smile, a snip, a plume"
    "of confetti. There is relief coiled in you so tightly it almost breaks free; you wanted something that could be counted on to stop water from taking people's roofs again. You wanted people to sleep without"
    "hearing the tide like a footstep at the door."
    "But the cameras only catch what looks decisive. They do not record the trades lost in the shadow of access roads, the raised walkways that reroute old paths, the Repair Garden's ledger that lists a lost"
    "plot for the new service road. They do not catch the way Jonah Reyes's hand trembles when he folds the ribbon into his palm and then pulls it away to avoid touching anything that smells of"
    "ceremony rather than salt."
    hide mayor_lynette_cole
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch9_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A camera shutter, then a long, approving silence from the assembled small crowd]
    show mayor_lynette_cole at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_lynette_cole "On three. One—two—three!"
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Scissors cut. Applause. The seawall stands, clean and decisive, between town and sea.]
    "Applause washes through you, immediate and thin. A prickle of triumph slides through your sternum like a foreign coin. Cassian 'Cass' Romano's gaze finds yours across the gap of people and cameras; his steel-gray eyes are"
    "bright in that specific way an engineer's eyes go bright when a model validates in the real world. There's triumph there, yes — but also calculation. You feel his hand brush yours as protocol and quiet"
    "congratulations folded into a single motion. The contact is warm and brief and carries all the compromise of the project: the desire to save lives, the necessity of structure, the cost."
    "Jonah Reyes's look is a different weather: flat, an amber that has been drained of its usual warmth and left with a hard, small light. He steps away from the podium as the press swarm, his shoulders small under the wool of his fisher's sweater."
    show jonah_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Did we save what mattered, Mira?"
    show mira_kestrel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We saved lives, Jonah. We bought time."

    jonah_reyes "Bought time by fencing in our mouths and changing how we work. That's not time — that's a lease."
    hide mayor_lynette_cole
    show cassian_cass_romano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "Jonah, we can adapt the slips. There are workarounds —"

    jonah_reyes "Workarounds are for when someone else's convenience doesn't match ours. This—' (he gestures toward the wall, toward the new access road slicing behind the Repair Garden) '—this changes the rhythm. Who decides those rhythms matters."

    cassian_cass_romano "We wrote local hiring and oversight into the contract. I can—"

    jonah_reyes "Can you write a grandfathered slip back in? Can you write a market back onto the boardwalk where my mother sold bait for three decades? Can you write back the garden that taught Tessa how to graft a salt-tolerant tomato?"
    "Cassian 'Cass' Romano's jaw tightens in a way you have seen in models when a variable refuses to converge: professional patience meeting a raw, local variable. He answers, softer, trying to reach past argument into repair."

    cassian_cass_romano "Not everything is reversible once it's built. But we can modify operations. We can create times and lanes for local crews. Give me a list — specific—"

    jonah_reyes "You mean — after we've already moved things out of their places. After the bulldozers have already cut into what we knew."

    mira_kestrel "Jonah. We put clauses in. I negotiated them. I told them about the garden. I—"

    jonah_reyes "And they were papers on a desk. Mira, I need to know that when a storm comes, I can get to my sons' boats without a bureaucrat's permission."
    "Tension cuts like a shell-splinter between you and Jonah Reyes. He looks at you not like an ally or an enemy but like someone who used to stand beside him at low tide, hands in nets,"
    "sharing the same small ritual. Now you have a different uniform — a jacket with embroidered tide lines — and where it once read as shared stewardship, it reads to him as a badge of capitulation."

    menu:
        "Take Jonah’s arm, steady him":
            "You reach out and take Jonah's elbow with the kind of small, domestic motion that used to mean ‘we'll fix this together.’ He flinches, then lets you lead him a few steps away from the crowd. For a fractured heartbeat you remember the boy who taught you to tie a proper knot."
        "Keep your distance and listen":
            "You let Jonah speak his piece without interrupting. Standing slightly back, you let the crowd and Cass's earnestness and the clicking cameras exist around you — a buffer. In the distance, the seawall's smooth face gleams like an accusation."

    # --- merge ---
    "(Whichever path you chose in that small private moment, the larger current does not change: the wall is up, commissioned, and the mechanisms that will make it enforceable — rules, gates, permits — are being set in motion.)"
    # [Scene: Boardwalk & Docks | Afternoon — the sun pushes through thin curtains of cloud]
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide mira_kestrel
    hide cassian_cass_romano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A nervous, dissonant piano motif underscoring the hum of town life]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Hammering, muffled conversations, gulls complaining overhead]
    "The town rearranges itself faster than you can run the new models again. Net-mending routines shift; a boy who used to run between stalls now has to go the long way around the service road; a"
    "vendor you knew from childhood sells pickled fish from behind a plastic awning instead of the sun-bleached table he used to have. The Repair Garden has a chain-link fence where a bed of heirloom beans used"
    "to bloom; a sign taped to the fence lists 'Access Road — Municipal Operations' in neat, official font."
    show tessa_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tessa_kestrel "They took our tomato bed. They said equipment access couldn't be blocked."
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We can petition—"

    tessa_kestrel "Petition how? With what? You put your name on the line, Mira. You signed the papers."

    mira_kestrel "I fought for clauses. For oversight. For jobs for our crews. I —"

    tessa_kestrel "You fought for contracts, not for gardens."
    "Tessa's words are a small, precise knife. They leave a burn. You wanted to balance scales no one else would hold, to thread community voice into the metal and concrete. But thread is not steel. You"
    "are beginning to understand what that means: that the instrumentality of an engineered defense reshapes even the hands that tend the town."
    show cassian_cass_romano at center:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "We can relocate some plots. Fund a community stewardship coordinator. Dr. Saira already has a proposal on adaptive garden mounts."

    tessa_kestrel "Adaptive. Great word for making us adapt to them."

    cassian_cass_romano "It's not perfect. But we avoided loss of life. We can make the operations humane."
    hide tessa_kestrel
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Humane isn't the word I used with my father when he told me to give up a net."
    "Cassian 'Cass' Romano turns to you after the conversation, his voice low where the microphones won't catch it."

    cassian_cass_romano "You did what you thought best. The engineering would have been useless if not for community buy-in. You made them trust it enough to sign — to let us build."

    mira_kestrel "I made them trust that we'd be careful. That we'd hold to our promises."

    cassian_cass_romano "And you'll hold them to it. You always do."
    "There is warmth in that exchange. A practical warmth, like two people who have stayed up with server logs and stress tests making quiet jokes at two in the morning. The warmth sits alongside something harsher;"
    "with every compromise you signed, a piece of the town's grammar — the way people move, where they meet, how children learn to read the sea — was redrafted into compliance documents and access maps. It"
    "is a heat and an ache that sits against your sternum like an ember."

    menu:
        "Let Cass take your hand in private":
            "You let him take your fingers. They are callused at the edges from spreadsheet scrawls and not from ropes, but the touch is solid and human. For a few breaths you allow a different kind of shelter. Then the noise of the docks returns and with it the detail of contracts."
        "Pull away; remind him of the promises":
            "You pull your hand back and remind him, quietly but sharply, of the timelines, the oversight clauses, the audits. The air between you cools into the precise professional warmth that has defined your partnership so far."

    # --- merge ---
    "(These small moments do not change the larger movement. They are flavor — human, necessary — in the stew of decisions and consequences.)"
    # [Scene: Docks and Access Gate | Night — Storm approaches, clouds thick and merciless]
    hide mira_kestrel
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch9_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rapid, percussion-heavy; alto strings sprinting]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain begins, then grows; gusts rattle signage; an urgent chatter on handheld radios]
    "The storm arrives on schedule and in excess — the sort of weather the models had predicted and the wall was designed to meet. The gauge on the municipal feed spikes. Water claws toward the town"
    "with a patient, practiced hunger. You stand at the seawall with Jonah Reyes and Cassian 'Cass' Romano and a thinning ring of municipal staff, Dr. Saira's face somewhere in the scatter of headlamps and reflective vests."
    "Instruments blink green. The parapets hold; the water that once would have licked at the backs of barrels now pauses, roared down by concrete. You feel relief as a physical, shock-like jolt. The wall does its"
    "job with a brutal grace. Cameras flash electronically as municipal dashboards flood with triumphant data."

    "But the storm also reveals the policy skeleton you've been stitching into the project. Automated gates at the slips lock certain access points during surge thresholds. The municipal protocol reads" "For safety and integrity of bulkhead operations, restricted access during storm surge to authorized vessels."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "They're locking the gate. My boys' boat is at Slip 4. It doesn't have 'authorization' because it's not registered to the company account. It never has been."

    "Radio Operator" "Protocol. We cannot risk unauthorized traffic on the service lane during an active surge."

    jonah_reyes "They're asking me to watch while the sea chews their boat. They're asking me to stand here while bureaucracy decides whose craft matters."
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "Jonah —"

    jonah_reyes "You put this wall here. You signed the control protocols. You let people who run gates decide which slips survive."
    "The words land like a physical blow. Around you, the storm makes everything already raw feel sharper. Cassian 'Cass' Romano steps between Jonah Reyes and the gate, voice urgent."
    show cassian_cass_romano at center:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "We didn't design it to be exclusionary. There's a manual override in the operations protocol — we can authorize emergency access."

    "Radio Operator" "Override must be issued by municipal operations under emergency clause — wait for confirmation."

    jonah_reyes "Wait for confirmation while the tide eats my sons' boat."
    "Mira Kestrel: (you move because you have always been a person of motion in crises) 'Give me the names. Give me registrations. I can push a temporary authorization.'"
    "You sprint to a tablet and begin to type, fingers slick with rain. The swarm of red and blue lights reflects in the screen. The authorization sequence demands credentials you don't have in the field. You"
    "can see, in a dozen places, the structure of safety forming an iron hand that will only open if the right bureaucratic key is used. You find Dr. Saira on your channel."
    hide jonah_reyes
    show dr_saira_ngoma at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_saira_ngoma "Mira, the clause is there. But it's under municipal control. Lynette's legal team insisted on the separation for liability."

    mira_kestrel "They're watching data, not faces. They're counting risk and not remembering who risk is for."

    dr_saira_ngoma "Issue a local exception. You can. You—"

    "Radio Operator" "Emergency override request received. Pending mayoral confirmation."
    hide mira_kestrel
    show mayor_lynette_cole at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_lynette_cole "We have teams on both sides. Manual overrides during surge are dangerous. We must follow protocol to maintain structural integrity."
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Maintain structural integrity — at the cost of people on our docks. Have you no idea what that sounds like?"
    "The storm is loud enough to swallow small pleas. You can feel Jonah Reyes's anger like heat. Cassian 'Cass' Romano's hand on your shoulder is a pragmatic anchor; you sense the ripple of his frustration and"
    "the professional fear beneath it. He knows the operational risk of ad hoc procedures during a surge. He also knows the human cost if you don't act. In the split-second decision that follows, the arousal in"
    "your chest is a live drum."
    "You find the override sequence by bypassing the municipal gateway and authorizing a temporary local exception tied to biometric confirmation and a promise of immediate audit. It's not pretty. It's a mess of code and raised"
    "eyebrows and the old, improvisational work of people who used to save boats with a knot and a shout rather than a server farm. You send it."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A long, thin beep. The gate begins to hum.]

    jonah_reyes "Now! Now! Pull them out!"
    "Local crews scramble. People shove into rain and wind and grease. For a ragged, breathless hour, bodies and ropes and curses move against the tide. The boats come out, skin slick with seawater, pilings spared. Someone"
    "rises on a winch and hollers a laugh that is half sob and half relief. The wall has done its job. The community has saved its own."
    "Then the radios hiccup. A legal directive is read aloud: the local exception will be logged and reviewed. Enforcement of access will be tightened after the surge to preserve the longevity of the structure. There will"
    "be penalties for unauthorized attempts. There will be scheduled windows for fishing crews. These are the things municipal bylaws sound like when they are written in the language of future-proofing."

    jonah_reyes "You saw them open the gate for us. You made them. You can make them again. But I don't want a repeated emergency to be the only time my crew can get in."
    hide dr_saira_ngoma
    show mira_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "I know. We'll make sure access schedules prioritize local crews."

    jonah_reyes "You said that before. You fought for it, and then the fine print built fences."
    hide mayor_lynette_cole
    show cassian_cass_romano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "Those fences are meant to keep this structure intact. If we allow uncontrolled traffic during multiple surges, the damage could be cumulative."

    jonah_reyes "And if we allow uncontrolled rules to be written by people who don't know the smell of fish, the town suﬀers."
    "The argument spirals into something less about practicalities and more about whose life counts in the ledger of safety. The adrenaline, the fear, the rain — everything sharpens now into a very high, combustible pitch. People"
    "shout. Someone slams a metal crate into the mud. A municipal officer grabs a clipboard like it is armor. Cassian 'Cass' Romano and Jonah Reyes face each other like two weather systems that will not merge."

    cassian_cass_romano "We can put community liaisons on shift rosters. I will ensure the contract specifies local access windows. Help me write them — sit at the table. Make them legally binding."

    jonah_reyes "Will you sit at the table, Mira? Or will you be at the engineers’ side when the next draft comes?"
    "You feel the weather of decisions collapsing into a storm of personhood: who you are to this town, to Jonah Reyes, to Cassian 'Cass' Romano. Cassian 'Cass' Romano's hand finds yours again, but this time the"
    "contact is neither shelter nor betrayal; it is an agreement signed in small gestures. Jonah Reyes turns away, pulling his hood up against the rain, and there is a finality in the way his shoulders fold"
    "inward."
    # [Scene: The Boardwalk | Dawn after the storm — wet, bright with a brittle sun]
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide mira_kestrel
    hide cassian_cass_romano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano, a slow descending line]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Gull calls, the soft scraping of nets, someone muttering a prayer]
    "In the light after, there is evidence of both salvation and loss. The wall stands with a bureaucrat's cold efficiency. Many lives are intact that would not be. Boats are bobbing again. The press calls it"
    "a triumph. Grant officers begin to draft replication proposals. There are checklists and medal ceremonies and the small, polite applause of officials."
    "But the Repair Garden's plot is barren under a temporary access strip. Vendors have been shifted. Tessa's tomato vines are missing. Jonah Reyes's smile is a paper thing, creased and hard to smooth."
    show tessa_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tessa_kestrel "Did we get enough? Will what we lost be replaced?"
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We saved people. We bought infrastructure. We wrote clauses that make people accountable."

    tessa_kestrel "But you signed away the way we lived. Is that replaceable?"
    "Cassian 'Cass' Romano finds you near the railing where the seawall's shadow meets the boardwalk's still-wet planks. There is a practical intimacy now — coffee shared between meetings, hands that steady charts, late-night edits on the"
    "contract language. It is not a love that unravels all your solitude; it is a partnership forged in spreadsheets and shared responsibility, and it offers you something like a place to put your fatigue."
    show cassian_cass_romano at center:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "We did the right thing under the circumstances. The models worked. The town is safer."

    mira_kestrel "Safer for some things. Less free in others."

    cassian_cass_romano "We can try to give those things back. Repairs, relocations, funding for the garden replants. It won't be the same. But we can create mitigations."

    mira_kestrel "Mitigations matter. But mitigations are not always repair."
    "You and Cassian 'Cass' Romano stand close enough that the warmth from his coat touches your sleeve. The nearness is a companionable refuge. You share a silence that is not empty — it is the press"
    "of two people who have chosen to make compromises together and to hold each other's hands through the accounting of consequences. It is enough, and it is not."
    "Jonah Reyes approaches, boots splashing in a puddle that rearranged itself overnight. He stops a few paces away, eyes steady but wet at the edges. He sets a hand against the rail and looks at you both."
    hide tessa_kestrel
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "I can't keep doing this, Mira. I can't be part of a system that only lets us in when it's convenient."

    mira_kestrel "Jonah—"

    jonah_reyes "You did what you thought was right. But right doesn't always look the same. For me, right smells like nets and plywood and the sound of my kids laughing on the deck. I don't recognize it in planning documents."
    "His words are not an accusation so much as a farewell framed as a truth he must live by. You have known this possibility in an abstract way since the first meeting, but now it is"
    "here, solid and physical. Jonah Reyes is not leaving because he hates you. He is leaving because the thing that tied him to the town — its grammar, the practiced choreography of days — has been"
    "rewritten in a language that does not hold his cadence."

    jonah_reyes "I have to find a way to keep the kids close to the boats we know. That might mean moving to a place where rules are written by people who fish."

    mira_kestrel "If you go, will you—"

    jonah_reyes "No. We love differently now. We tried to make the town safer, and you made hard choices. I can't stand in a place that's safer but no longer ours in the way that matters."

    cassian_cass_romano "Jonah, I respect your roots. If there's anything I can do to—"

    jonah_reyes "You can do the thing you do: build things. But don't try to build my memory back."
    "He walks away then, not with the slam of a door but with the small, steady footing of someone who has chosen another map. You watch the line of his back diminish into the community he"
    "loves. Something in you folds shut; it is not rage now but a hollowing. The seawall glitters behind you — a success and a wound."

    menu:
        "Run after Jonah, ask him to stay":
            "You take two steps, then stop. Your voice finds him — a plea tied up in apology and love. He pauses, looks back, his face a map of decision, and then he continues, leaving you with the echo of the promise you can't keep for him."
        "Let him go, and walk with Cass to draft mitigation plans":
            "You stay. You let Jonah go and you walk with Cass toward Municipal Hall. There are clauses to write, community liaison roles to draft. You choose the work of repair, knowing it will not stitch everything back together."

    # --- merge ---
    "(Whatever small, private action you chose does not alter the arc of what occurred: Jonah leaves in search of a life that matches his dignity; you remain tethered to the compromise that saved many but also edited the town you loved.)"
    # [Scene: Boardwalk | Late Afternoon — Golden hour but with a brittle edge]
    hide mira_kestrel
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch9_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Single cello line, low, then resolving to an unresolved cadence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Children laughing quietly; a distant saw; the sea turning its shoulder away]
    "You stand at the railing where the seawall meets the boardwalk. The coral pendant at your throat feels almost foreign now — cooled by the wind, glass catching an iron light. You think of the lives"
    "spared by the wall: of households that still have roofs, of children who did not have to learn to fear sleep. You count these things like prayers. You also count what was edited out of the"
    "town's syntax: the informal crossings, the garden beds, the small businesses pushed behind a service lane."
    "Your nights are filled with model validations and apology letters and community hearings where you listen until your jaw aches. You write amendments and amendments write you. The intimacy with Cassian 'Cass' Romano is steady, quiet"
    "— meetings that linger into coffee and then into sheets of shared spreadsheets. It is a warmth that keeps a cold place at bay, practical and human. But every time Jonah Reyes's amber gaze slides past"
    "you in a memory, the warmth cools."
    "You think of Old Man Rafi's stories about tides as a kind of grammar taught to kids: the sea speaks and the town answers. Today the town speaks with permits and gates and audit trails. It"
    "is an answer that keeps people dry. It is an answer that also redraws sentences."
    show cassian_cass_romano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_cass_romano "We did what we had to. The funding means we can stabilize the town for decades."
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We stabilized a shoreline but not a village."

    cassian_cass_romano "Then we rebuild what we can. Fund the garden. Make permanent access windows for crews. Make it so Jonah's family can fish without waiting for an emergency."

    mira_kestrel "He wanted a place that recognized his work as valuable in every weather. That recognition isn't just scheduling. It's the town's bones."

    cassian_cass_romano "Bones can be rebuilt. Systems can be designed humanely. Let us do that."
    "You want to believe him. You want to fold into the pragmatic, tender work of making mitigations that matter. You want to feel whole again. But there is a grief in you now that is not"
    "temporary. It is a very negative, deep ache that smells like a storm that took more than your roof: it took an idiom, a set of small freedoms, a pattern of mornings that you and Jonah"
    "shared. That loss thrums beneath the accomplishment like a second tide."
    "You close your leather notebook and press the coral pendant, feeling it cold and unyielding. Pride and private grief sit side by side; they are not reconcilable, only held together like two stones that bear silent"
    "friction. You saved the town from a flood that would have swallowed roofs and memory. You did not save everything you loved about how the town breathed."
    hide cassian_cass_romano
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch9_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single held cello note that does not resolve, then fades into the sound of the sea]
    "You stand there until the light shifts into a bruise and the town moves around you in battered, careful rhythm. There are speeches to give, audits to oversee, gardens to replant, liaisons to hire. There is"
    "also the knowledge that some things cannot be grafted back once the bulldozers have run. You will keep working; you will keep fighting for mitigations and oversight and restorative funding. You will call in favors and"
    "prod the municipal machine until it grinds into better shape."
    "But you will also carry the private hollow — a very negative ache that will not allow full satisfaction. The wall held. Lives were saved. Yet the town's old grammar is edited, and part of you"
    "went with it: the small, unascribed rituals that mapped identity and belonging. You have gained safety and sacrificed syntax. You have gained a partner who can draft contracts and share late nights, and lost the unpolished"
    "intimacy of shared nets with the person who once mapped the same tide-lines with you."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_9 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
